# Samuel Rucker

**Samuel Rucker** (born 1949) is an American politician and former educator who served as a member of the [California State Assembly](/California_State_Assembly), representing the 65th district from 1996 to 2002. A member of the [Democratic Party](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)), his tenure was marked by a focus on educational reform, urban development, and community advocacy. Before his election to the State Assembly, Rucker had a long career in public education, rising to the position of high school principal.

## Early Life and Education

Samuel Rucker was born on March 12, 1949, in [Los Angeles, California](/Los_Angeles), to a family of modest means. His father worked as a mechanic and his mother as a seamstress. Growing up in the [Crenshaw](/Crenshaw,_Los_Angeles) neighborhood, Rucker was a product of the [Los Angeles Unified School District](/Los_Angeles_Unified_School_District) (LAUSD), attending local public schools from elementary through high school. This experience profoundly shaped his later political views on public education.

He was the first in his family to attend college, enrolling at [California State University, Dominguez Hills](/California_State_University,_Dominguez_Hills) in 1967. There, he majored in [History](/History) and participated in the [Educational Opportunity Program](/Educational_Opportunity_Program), which provided him with critical academic and financial support. Rucker graduated with a Bachelor of Arts in 1971. He later earned a Master's degree in [Educational Administration](/Educational_administration) from [Pepperdine University](/Pepperdine_University) in 1982.

During his college years, Rucker was deeply influenced by the social and political movements of the late 1960s and early 1970s, including the [Civil Rights Movement](/Civil_Rights_Movement) and the [Chicano Movement](/Chicano_Movement). He became an advocate for student rights and greater diversity in the curriculum.

## Career in Education

After completing his bachelor's degree, Rucker began his career as a [history teacher](/History_education) at [Drew Middle School](/Drew_Middle_School) in the [Compton Unified School District](/Compton_Unified_School_District) in 1972. He was known for his engaging teaching style and his ability to connect with students from disadvantaged backgrounds. He often incorporated primary source documents and encouraged critical discussions about local and national history.

In 1983, he moved to [Long Beach Unified School District](/Long_Beach_Unified_School_District), accepting a position as a teacher at [Jordan High School](/Jordan_High_School_(Long_Beach,_California)). His leadership skills were quickly recognized, and he was promoted to assistant principal in 1987. Rucker earned a reputation as a firm but fair administrator who was committed to improving academic standards and reducing the dropout rate.

In 1993, he was appointed principal of [Washington Preparatory High School](/Washington_Preparatory_High_School) in the [Inglewood Unified School District](/Inglewood_Unified_School_District). His tenure there was transformative. He implemented several innovative programs, including a college-preparatory track for all students and a partnership with local businesses for vocational training. His success at Washington Prep solidified his standing as a prominent figure in local educational circles and laid the groundwork for his political career.

## California State Assembly (1996–2002)

### 1996 Election

In 1996, Rucker announced his candidacy for the [California State Assembly](/California_State_Assembly) in the newly redrawn 65th district, which included parts of [South Los Angeles](/South_Los_Angeles), [Compton](/Compton,_California), and [Long Beach](/Long_Beach,_California). The district had a large [African-American](/African_Americans) and [Latino](/Latino) population. Rucker ran on a platform of "Education First," promising to secure more funding for public schools and reform the state's [Standardized Testing](/Standardized_test) system.

He faced a crowded Democratic primary but won with a strong grassroots campaign heavily supported by teachers' unions and community organizations. In the general election, he defeated his [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) opponent with over 75% of the vote, a testament to the district's strong Democratic leanings.

### First Term (1997–1998)

Upon taking office, Rucker was assigned to the Assembly [Education Committee](/California_State_Assembly_Committee_on_Education) and the [Appropriations Committee](/California_State_Assembly_Committee_on_Appropriations). His first major legislative victory was the passage of the "Rucker Class Size Reduction Act" (Assembly Bill 102), which allocated funds to lower K-3 class sizes in urban districts. He also became a vocal opponent of [Proposition 227](/Proposition_227), a 1998 ballot initiative that sought to eliminate bilingual education in California. Rucker argued the proposition was "a solution in search of a problem" that would harm [English Language Learners](/English_language_learner).

### Second Term (1999–2000)

Re-elected in 1998 with an increased majority, Rucker took on a more prominent role. He became the chair of the [Assembly Sub-Committee on Education Finance](/California_State_Assembly_Committee_on_Education). During this period, he championed legislation to increase the state's [minimum wage](/Minimum_wage_in_the_United_States), arguing that many school support staff were struggling to live in the state they served. He also worked on bipartisan efforts to fund after-school programs, emphasizing their role in reducing juvenile crime.

His legislative style was described as "pragmatic but passionate." While he was a staunch [liberal](/Liberalism_in_the_United_States), he was known for working across the aisle with moderate Republicans on issues related to workforce development and infrastructure.

### Third Term and Committee Leadership (2001–2002)

In his final term, Rucker was appointed Vice Chair of the powerful [Assembly Ways and Means Committee](/California_State_Assembly_Ways_and_Means_Committee). This position gave him significant influence over the state budget. He used this leverage to secure funding for the "Digital Divide Initiative," which aimed to provide computers and internet access to low-income schools.

One of his most significant and controversial achievements was his work on [Assembly Bill 1771](/California_State_Assembly_Bill_1771), which reformed the state's [school funding formula](/School_funding_in_the_United_States) to provide more resources to districts with high concentrations of poverty and [English Language Learners](/English_language_learner). The bill faced strong opposition from wealthier suburban districts but was ultimately signed into law by Governor [Gray Davis](/Gray_Davis).

## Political Positions and Legacy

Rucker was a classic [New Deal](/New_Deal)-style [liberal](/Liberalism_in_the_United_States). His core beliefs centered on the idea that government had a moral obligation to provide a robust social safety net and ensure equal opportunity, particularly through public education.

*   **Education:** He was a staunch defender of public schools and opposed the expansion of [school vouchers](/School_vouchers). He believed in increasing teacher pay and professional development as keys to improving student outcomes.
*   **Social Justice:** He was a vocal critic of racial profiling and supported legislation to reform the [criminal justice system](/Criminal_justice_in_the_United_States).
*   **Environment:** Representing a district with significant industrial activity and port traffic, he supported stricter [air quality](/Air_quality) regulations and was an early advocate for transitioning to [zero-emission vehicles](/Zero-emission_vehicle).

His legacy is primarily tied to his work on educational equity. The funding reforms he helped pass are still a part of California's school finance system, and the after-school programs he championed have been credited with helping generations of students in underserved communities.

## Later Life and Family

Rucker chose not to seek re-election in 2002, citing a desire to return to private life and spend more time with his family. He was succeeded in the Assembly by [Isadore Hall](/Isadore_Hall).

After leaving politics, Rucker served on the board of several non-profit organizations focused on youth development and civic engagement. He has also been a frequent guest lecturer at the [University of California, Los Angeles](/University_of_California,_Los_Angeles) (UCLA) School of Education, discussing the intersection of policy and classroom practice.

He is married to Eleanor Rucker, a retired social worker. They have two adult children and four grandchildren. The Ruckers reside in the [Baldwin Hills](/Baldwin_Hills,_Los_Angeles) neighborhood of Los Angeles. In his retirement, he is an avid gardener and a dedicated follower of [L.A. Dodgers](/Los_Angeles_Dodgers) baseball.